Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.279
&gt;&gt; ALLEN: I'm Peter Allen. And I'm the director
of Google University. And Meng asked to me

00:00:06.279 --> 00:00:13.150
introduce Daniel Goleman to you. Daniel Goleman
presents a challenge to us at Google. Having

00:00:13.150 --> 00:00:17.699
recently been hired here myself and having
worked on hiring others, I know how sharply

00:00:17.699 --> 00:00:23.570
we focus on the quantitative evidence of intellect.
We look hard at grades and standardized test

00:00:23.570 --> 00:00:29.150
scores because we believe they demonstrate
ability and predict success at Google. Now,

00:00:29.150 --> 00:00:35.320
IQ matters, of course, but Daniel Goleman
has based his career as a writer and psychologist

00:00:35.320 --> 00:00:40.880
on the argument that IQ is only a part of
what makes people succeed in their work and

00:00:40.880 --> 00:00:47.751
personal lives and not necessarily the most
important part either. In his books, Dr. Goleman

00:00:47.751 --> 00:00:55.210
addresses the role that emotions such as anger,
humor, anxiety, optimism, melancholy, and

00:00:55.210 --> 00:01:02.450
happiness play in all aspects of our lives.
He argues also that people can learn how to

00:01:02.450 --> 00:01:07.900
manage these emotions and that we therefore
have the power to transform our relationship

00:01:07.900 --> 00:01:13.750
with our emotions and through them the relationships
we have with our colleagues, our families,

00:01:13.750 --> 00:01:19.940
and our friends. Perhaps most interestingly,
he also argues that relationships have the

00:01:19.940 --> 00:01:27.659
power to mold not only human experience, but
also human biology. In his belief that the

00:01:27.659 --> 00:01:33.000
power of education and in his belief in the
power of education that--in his belief that

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:38.620
positive characteristics like empathy are
innate, Dr. Goleman reveals that he is fundamentally

00:01:38.620 --> 00:01:44.440
an optimist. What distinguishes Daniel Goleman
from old line proponents of positive thinking,

00:01:44.440 --> 00:01:50.950
however, is his grounding in psychology and
neuroscience. Armed with a Ph.D. in psychology

00:01:50.950 --> 00:01:56.170
from Harvard and a first-rate journalism background
at the New York Times, Dr. Goleman has authored

00:01:56.170 --> 00:02:01.770
half a dozen books that explore the physical
and chemical workings of the brain and their

00:02:01.770 --> 00:02:07.490
relationships with what we experience as everyday
life. His most recent book is called "Social

00:02:07.490 --> 00:02:13.439
Intelligence: The New Science of Human Relationships."
In addition to his writing, he has also played

00:02:13.439 --> 00:02:18.950
important roles in numerous organizations,
including the Collaborative for Academics,

00:02:18.950 --> 00:02:24.529
Social and Emotional Learning and the Mind
 &amp; Life Institute. The American Psychological

00:02:24.529 --> 00:02:29.810
Association has given him its career achievement
award for journalism and he's also been elected

00:02:29.810 --> 00:02:35.819
a fellow of the American Association for the
Advancement of Science. Dr. Goleman's talk

00:02:35.819 --> 00:02:42.730
today draws on recent data from cognitive
and brain science to show how emotional intelligence

00:02:42.730 --> 00:02:49.269
adds to the IQ intelligence of which most
of us today here are more familiar. He will

00:02:49.269 --> 00:02:57.599
show that skills such as self-awareness, emotional
mastery, motivation, empathy, and social effectiveness

00:02:57.599 --> 00:03:04.079
have a greater impact than raw intelligence
on career success, outstanding individual

00:03:04.079 --> 00:03:10.319
performance, leadership, and the creation
of successful teams. I'm feeling myself become

00:03:10.319 --> 00:03:15.840
smarter, more empathetic and more self-aware
already, and I'm delighted to introduce Daniel

00:03:15.840 --> 00:03:19.269
Goleman to Google and Google to Daniel Goleman.
Let's hear what he has to say.

00:03:19.269 --> 00:03:32.639
&gt;&gt; GOLEMAN: Thank you, Peter, for that very
kind introduction. But, first, a disclaimer,

00:03:32.639 --> 00:03:38.870
just hearing about this is not going to make
anybody more emotionally and socially intelligent.

00:03:38.870 --> 00:03:46.989
It might interest you in pursuing some of
this. What I want to do is build the case

00:03:46.989 --> 00:03:55.900
that these soft skills have hard value in
an environment, of work environment like this.

00:03:55.900 --> 00:04:08.900
Even though the culture of tech may not necessarily
explicitly value things like empathy or other

00:04:08.900 --> 00:04:15.969
elements of emotional intelligence, implicitly,
this is what makes people highly effective

00:04:15.969 --> 00:04:23.159
no matter what they do. And I want to give
you the neuroscience behind this and some

00:04:23.159 --> 00:04:29.919
concepts that might help you rethink what
the elements of success are in the work place.

00:04:29.919 --> 00:04:39.940
So here is the question. What is the relationship
between raw intellect, IQ, and the other metrics

00:04:39.940 --> 00:04:47.349
of IQ, and emotional intelligence? So, by
emotional intelligence, I mean how we handle

00:04:47.349 --> 00:04:54.470
ourselves, how we handle our relationships,
the soft side ability. I'm going to argue

00:04:54.470 --> 00:05:01.900
that, because of the way the brain is structured,
these soft skills have hard consequence because

00:05:01.900 --> 00:05:08.449
they are catalytic for whatever other abilities
we have. They allow us to make the best use

00:05:08.449 --> 00:05:16.830
of them, to apply them, and to leverage them.
Now, here's an interesting way of thinking

00:05:16.830 --> 00:05:28.020
about it. If you were to do a scatter plot
of a large population sample and you did IQ

00:05:28.020 --> 00:05:34.110
against emotional intelligence, they're roughly
independent, so, you get a kind of a random

00:05:34.110 --> 00:05:42.919
distribution. Now, if you take this pool and
you map it on Google, or any other company

00:05:42.919 --> 00:05:50.659
that hires, that places a premium on cognitive
abilities, this is the total sample. What

00:05:50.659 --> 00:05:57.480
you've done is really interesting because
