00:06:05.650 --> 00:06:13.540
difference for IQ, a very little variation
in the population at the very top and a very

00:06:13.540 --> 00:06:19.600
large difference for emotional intelligence.
That means that whatever emotional intelligence

00:06:19.600 --> 00:06:28.139
contributes to success in an environment like
this, it matters more per unit than IQ does.

00:06:28.139 --> 00:06:36.810
So there's actually a floor effect here for
IQ. You wouldn't expect that IQ alone is going

00:06:36.810 --> 00:06:42.659
to help you be highly effective in this work
environment because it's not that much different

00:06:42.659 --> 00:06:53.009
from every other IQ on the floor. Interesting.
I was having a conversation with a guy on

00:06:53.009 --> 00:06:58.849
a plane next to me once. He turned out to
be on the board of trustees at MIT. And he

00:06:58.849 --> 00:07:05.759
said, "You know, the real job of the board
of trustee at a place like MIT is fundraising.

00:07:05.759 --> 00:07:13.090
And we did an internal study of alumnus of
MIT to see who are our biggest donors and

00:07:13.090 --> 00:07:17.849
what did they look like as students." And
he said, "You know what we found? It wasn't

00:07:17.849 --> 00:07:23.969
the quants, the 4.0s, the people who were
absolutely brilliant all the way through school

00:07:23.969 --> 00:07:30.849
who ended up being so successful that they
could give us hundreds of millions of dollars.

00:07:30.849 --> 00:07:36.740
It was people who were good enough to get
in and good enough to stay and then get through,

00:07:36.740 --> 00:07:41.999
who had other abilities already. They were
team captains, club presidents. They were

00:07:41.999 --> 00:07:47.629
starting their own businesses on the side
already as undergrads. Those were the people

00:07:47.629 --> 00:07:53.229
who became the founders and heads of companies
that grew to be big enough that they could

00:07:53.229 --> 00:07:59.090
afford to become our biggest donors at MIT."
When I was at the graduate school at Harvard,

00:07:59.090 --> 00:08:09.039
they did a study, interesting study of how
well your graduate school entry exams predicted

00:08:09.039 --> 00:08:15.930
success in that career. They did that in the
business school, medical school, law school,

00:08:15.930 --> 00:08:23.599
ed school. And does anybody care to hazard
a guess as to what the correlation is between,

00:08:23.599 --> 00:08:28.230
say, GMATs, GREs and career success?
