00:08:57.130 --> 00:09:02.320
that's been found in hundreds of studies is
somewhere around 0.2. That means that it accounts

00:09:02.320 --> 00:09:10.370
for four percent of the variation. It's a
very small factor. But to look at it in another

00:09:10.370 --> 00:09:16.560
way in an organization like this, I'd like
to introduce you to a concept that was developed

00:09:16.560 --> 00:09:22.400
by a professor of mine in Harvard named David
McClelland that's a notion of a competence.

00:09:22.400 --> 00:09:30.090
He said--back in the ‘70s, he wrote what
was then a very radical paper in the main

00:09:30.090 --> 00:09:35.630
psychology journal--he said, “If you want
to hire the best person for a job, any job,

00:09:35.630 --> 00:09:40.950
don't look at their GPA, don't look at their
IQ, don't look at their personality test.

00:09:40.950 --> 00:09:48.160
Instead, begin by looking in your own organization
people who now or in the past held that job,

00:09:48.160 --> 00:09:53.440
the one the person is applying for, identify
it by any metric that makes sense, the top

00:09:53.440 --> 00:09:59.340
10 percent, the star performers, compare them
to people who are only average in the systematic

00:09:59.340 --> 00:10:04.930
method. Identify the traits or competencies
or abilities you find in the stars and not

00:10:04.930 --> 00:10:10.430
in the average and hire people who look like
the stars.” That's called competence modeling

00:10:10.430 --> 00:10:18.180
now. It's a very widespread methodology among
world class organizations who use it to find

00:10:18.180 --> 00:10:23.680
out who should be—who should we be hiring,
who should we be promoting, what should we

00:10:23.680 --> 00:10:29.850
help people develop so that we can be successful
as a company. When I wrote a follow-up book

00:10:29.850 --> 00:10:35.040
to Emotional Intelligence, I looked at a couple
of hundred of those models and I was interested

00:10:35.040 --> 00:10:41.100
basically in one thing only, and that was
how many of the competencies that have been

00:10:41.100 --> 00:10:48.450
developed, identified independently by companies
around the world and in many different sectors

00:10:48.450 --> 00:10:59.740
are purely cognitive, IQ-like abilities, and
how many mix cognitive and emotional capacities?

00:10:59.740 --> 00:11:04.570
And those are the emotional intelligence ones.
And I found that for jobs of all kinds at

00:11:04.570 --> 00:11:11.310
basically at every level, these emotional
intelligence competencies were more important

00:11:11.310 --> 00:11:16.080
in predicting who would become outstanding.
That ratio was about two to one. The higher

00:11:16.080 --> 00:11:20.520
you went in the organization, the more it
matters. So, for top leaders, you look at

00:11:20.520 --> 00:11:27.010
a competence model of the abilities that we've
identified in outstanding leaders. Here, 80

00:11:27.010 --> 00:11:33.910
to 90 percent of them are in the emotional
intelligence domain. IQ turns out to be a

00:11:33.910 --> 00:11:38.890
threshold ability--particularly, of course,
here with Google, it's explicitly so. You

00:11:38.890 --> 00:11:45.480
need to be smart enough to get in the game.
Once you're in the game however, what is it

00:11:45.480 --> 00:11:50.870
that is going to allow you to become an emergent
leader and going to allow you to become the

00:11:50.870 --> 00:11:58.920
person who is most effective? And, here, it
turns out these other abilities start to factor

00:11:58.920 --> 00:12:03.220
in a major way. These are what are called
distinguishing competencies. And I'll read

00:12:03.220 --> 00:12:10.080
you the top six distinguishing competencies
among star performers. This is for individual

00:12:10.080 --> 00:12:14.540
contributors in the tech sector. And is kind
of an aggregate of studies that's been done

00:12:14.540 --> 00:12:21.660
in many different tech companies. And you
can tell me if it makes any sense here. The

00:12:21.660 --> 00:12:31.990
number one competence that distinguishes stars
from average is the singular drive to achieve,

00:12:31.990 --> 00:12:37.940
to improve performance, to make whatever I'm
working on better, faster, quicker, more powerful,

00:12:37.940 --> 00:12:46.500
more effective. And the sign of this competence
is that people who have it have very high

00:12:46.500 --> 00:12:53.260
internal standards for success. They're not
really driven by what other people say matters;

00:12:53.260 --> 00:12:59.100
it's that they themselves know how good something
should be. And they hold themselves to that

00:12:59.100 --> 00:13:04.500
standard. You work long hours to achieve that
standard. It's very compelling. People who

00:13:04.500 --> 00:13:10.570
have this like to keep score. You like metrics.
You want to know where you are now: Are you

00:13:10.570 --> 00:13:17.221
better or worse? How much better can you be?
Well, doing this help make it better. Another

00:13:17.221 --> 00:13:22.931
sign of this is setting challenging goals.
People who are innovative have this ability.

00:13:22.931 --> 00:13:31.630
Does this make any sense? Yeah? It resonates.
Okay, that's number one. Number two is impact

