00:22:26.380 --> 00:22:30.980
abilities, which integrate the executive center
and the emotional centers because it's not

00:22:30.980 --> 00:22:36.130
just the amygdala, it's an extended network
through the hippocampus and other elements.

00:22:36.130 --> 00:22:41.570
The amygdala is very widely connected throughout
the brain. So, when I talk about emotional

00:22:41.570 --> 00:22:46.680
intelligence at the neural level, I'm talking
about this cortical, neocortical, actually

00:22:46.680 --> 00:22:55.900
prefrontal, subcortical integration of abilities.
Now, there are four parts to emotional intelligence.

00:22:55.900 --> 00:23:00.220
There are four different domains. The first
two--oh, I forgot something really important.

00:23:00.220 --> 00:23:07.240
Prefrontal cortex, while I'm on the subject,
it turns out that when the amygdala hijacks,

00:23:07.240 --> 00:23:12.790
it drives and takes over the right side of
the prefrontal cortex. If you do a brain imaging

00:23:12.790 --> 00:23:17.480
when someone is having a hijack, someone is
really scared or angry, you see a lot of activity

00:23:17.480 --> 00:23:23.790
in the amygdala and related circuits and a
lot of activity on the right. When we're feeling

00:23:23.790 --> 00:23:32.110
good, we're having a great day, we're... good
energy, I could take on anything, very enthusiastic

00:23:32.110 --> 00:23:36.490
and so on, you see a very different picture
in the prefrontal cortex, the right is quiet

00:23:36.490 --> 00:23:42.870
and the left is hardly active. Each of us--it's
been discovered by a fellow named Richard

00:23:42.870 --> 00:23:49.760
Davidson at the University of Wisconsin--each
of us has a resting ratio of right to left

00:23:49.760 --> 00:23:55.400
activation that predicts quite accurately
our mood range day to day. There's a bell

00:23:55.400 --> 00:24:00.929
curve for it. Most of us are in the middle.
We have good days, we have bad days. If you're

00:24:00.929 --> 00:24:06.850
very far to the right, it means that you are
probably clinically depressed or have an anxiety

00:24:06.850 --> 00:24:13.480
disorder. If you're very far to the left,
things just roll off you. You hardly ever

00:24:13.480 --> 00:24:22.120
have a bad day. And what the left does that
the right does not do is have an inhibitory

00:24:22.120 --> 00:24:28.420
circuit for the amygdala. So, the amygdala
sends out these thoughts that could become

00:24:28.420 --> 00:24:32.860
what are called depressogenic thoughts, something
really upsetting or that could provoke an

00:24:32.860 --> 00:24:38.360
anxiety or make you really angry. And the
left prefrontal cortex basically says, "Shut

00:24:38.360 --> 00:24:46.050
up. I don't want to... I don't need to hear
that now," and it clams the amygdala. So,

00:24:46.050 --> 00:24:55.059
people who have this ability have more good
days, more high energy, more self-confidence,

00:24:55.059 --> 00:25:05.050
more enthusiasm and better moods, basically.
So, the first two elements of emotional intelligence

00:25:05.050 --> 00:25:11.140
have to do with self mastery. And they are
based--this circuitry is the neuro platform.

00:25:11.140 --> 00:25:16.330
The first of these is self-awareness--knowing
what I'm feeling, knowing why I'm feeling

00:25:16.330 --> 00:25:24.890
it. Self-awareness is very important for decision-making,
particularly personal decision-making, but

00:25:24.890 --> 00:25:29.730
also business or even technical decision-making
for quite an interesting reason. There was

00:25:29.730 --> 00:25:39.950
a study done by a man named Antonio Damasio.
He is now at UCS. He's an expert on this circuitry.

00:25:39.950 --> 00:25:51.980
And because he is an expert on this circuitry,
a very bright corporate lawyer who unfortunately

00:25:51.980 --> 00:25:58.970
had a prefrontal brain tumor which was operated
on quite successfully and early but during

00:25:58.970 --> 00:26:06.900
surgery they snipped the connection between
the amygdala and the PFC. This lawyer went

00:26:06.900 --> 00:26:17.720
to see Damasio because his life was collapsing.
And Damasio tested him and couldn't see anything

00:26:17.720 --> 00:26:25.900
wrong. The lawyer's life had collapsed in
this way. He seemed to be able to function

00:26:25.900 --> 00:26:31.460
just as well after surgery as before, but
he couldn't keep his job. He lost his job.

00:26:31.460 --> 00:26:34.900
He couldn't keep any job. His wife left him.
He lost his house. He ended up living in his

00:26:34.900 --> 00:26:38.720
brother's spare bedroom. And, in despair,
he goes to Damasio. He says, "Well, you're

00:26:38.720 --> 00:26:43.429
an expert on the circuitry, can you figure
out what's wrong with me?" Damasio gives him

00:26:43.429 --> 00:26:48.650
a battery of neuropsychological tests. Nothing
wrong. Attention, memory, just as good as

00:26:48.650 --> 00:26:56.990
before surgery. IQ was very high still after
surgery as it was before. But he couldn't

00:26:56.990 --> 00:27:03.111
keep a job. And then Damasio got a clue. He
asked him this question: When shall we have

00:27:03.111 --> 00:27:08.800
our next appointment? He realized that the
lawyer could give him the rational pros and

00:27:08.800 --> 00:27:14.510
cons of every hour for the next two weeks,
but he didn't know which was best. In other

00:27:14.510 --> 00:27:23.240
words, Damasio argues, when we have a thought,
our emotional centers valence it for us. When

00:27:23.240 --> 00:27:32.670
we're making a decision, our emotional centers
prioritize for us. He no longer had that ability.

00:27:32.670 --> 00:27:38.910
Damasio argues that in order to make a good
decision--you know, which strategy should

00:27:38.910 --> 00:27:48.530
we follow, should our team go for plan A or
plan B, how does this guy compared to the,

00:27:48.530 --> 00:27:53.910
you know, X other guys I've dated, should
I marry this guy or not, should I leave this

00:27:53.910 --> 00:28:02.990
job for another--all of those decisions depend
on our ability to draw on the wisdom of the

00:28:02.990 --> 00:28:06.911
emotions. The wisdom of emotions is not just
a pretty phrase. It actually refers to something

00:28:06.911 --> 00:28:16.360
that goes on very low in the brain, in the
basal ganglia, its base brain. The basal ganglia

00:28:16.360 --> 00:28:23.290
absorbs everything we do in life, every situation
and extracts decisions rules. That worked,

00:28:23.290 --> 00:28:27.500
that didn't work. When I said that, I really
blew it. When I said that, it really worked.

00:28:27.500 --> 00:28:34.760
Our life wisdom on any topic is stored in
the basal ganglia. The basal ganglia is so

00:28:34.760 --> 00:28:41.980
primitive that it has zero connectivity to
the verbal cortex. It can't tell us what it

00:28:41.980 --> 00:28:47.670
knows in words. It tells us in feelings, has
a lot of connectivity, the emotional centers

00:28:47.670 --> 00:28:54.429
of the brain and to the gut. And it tells
us this is right or this is wrong as a gut

00:28:54.429 --> 00:29:02.850
feeling. So part of self-awareness is the
ability to tune in to those subtle feelings.

00:29:02.850 --> 00:29:08.910
And this is very important for example, not
just in decisions but when it comes to ethics

00:29:08.910 --> 00:29:14.070
and integrity. The answer to the question
is what I'm about to do in keeping with my

00:29:14.070 --> 00:29:18.830
sense of ethics--meaning, priorities, values
or whatever. It doesn't come to us verbally.

00:29:18.830 --> 00:29:25.170
It comes to us through the same nonverbal
neural system. And we've got to be able to

00:29:25.170 --> 00:29:36.500
attune to feeling to read yes or no. So it's
a kind of moral rudder, too, in life. The

00:29:36.500 --> 00:29:45.490
second ability in emotional intelligence is
managing emotions. And managing emotions really

00:29:45.490 --> 00:29:50.160
has to do with our inhibitory ability. I don't
mean managing all emotions. I mean managing

00:29:50.160 --> 00:29:58.170
the disturbing, crippling, dysphoric emotions,
the ones that get in the way, because emotions

00:29:58.170 --> 00:30:03.490
of course are what make life rich. You want
to mobilize your passions. In fact, the center

00:30:03.490 --> 00:30:11.480
for motivation for maintaining goal and pursuing
it is in the left prefrontal cortex. The left

00:30:11.480 --> 00:30:19.890
prefrontal cortex with the connection to the
hippocampus as a node for memory is what helps

00:30:19.890 --> 00:30:24.770
us keep in mind how good we're going to feel
when we finish this. And that's probably very

00:30:24.770 --> 00:30:30.970
important around here, I think, because if
you don't have that capacity to keep reminding

00:30:30.970 --> 00:30:38.490
you about how it's going to feel, you give
up. So, motivation very much depends on this

00:30:38.490 --> 00:30:48.240
circuitry. Another ability has to do with
how--with the relationship between emotionality,

00:30:48.240 --> 00:30:53.679
impulsiveness and learning. There was a study
done just down the road here, at Stanford,

00:30:53.679 --> 00:31:00.110
many years ago with four-year-olds, kids in
Stanford preschool. And these are children

00:31:00.110 --> 00:31:06.299
of professors and graduate of Stanford. And
each kid was brought in the room one by one,

00:31:06.299 --> 00:31:12.523
sat down at a small table, and a big juicy
marshmallow was put in front of them. And

00:31:12.523 --> 00:31:16.880
the experimenter says to the kids, “You
can have this marshmallow now if you want,

00:31:16.880 --> 00:31:22.861
but of you wait to eat till I come back for
running an errand, you can have two of that.”

00:31:22.861 --> 00:31:29.710
Then the experimenter leaves the room. This
is a situation, a predicament really that

00:31:29.710 --> 00:31:35.160
tries the souls of any four-year-old, I think.
&gt;&gt; Or for the rest of us.

00:31:35.160 --> 00:31:40.390
&gt;&gt; GOLEMAN: Or the rest of us for that matter,
yeah. And I've seen the footage. It's very

00:31:40.390 --> 00:31:44.130
funny. Some of the kids will smell it and
then jump away like it was very dangerous.

00:31:44.130 --> 00:31:50.960
Some kids go off in the corner and sing and
dance to distract themselves. About a third

00:31:50.960 --> 00:31:56.620
of the kids wait out the endless four or five
minutes till, you know, the experimenter comes

00:31:56.620 --> 00:32:01.450
back and they get the two. And about a third
couldn't stand it. They just gobble it down

00:32:01.450 --> 00:32:07.040
on the spot. But the payoff finding came fourteen
years later. These kids are tracked down as

00:32:07.040 --> 00:32:12.000
they're about to graduate high school. And
the two groups are compared--the kids who

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:17.340
grabbed and the ones who waited. Very interesting,
kind of, staggering differences it turns out

00:32:17.340 --> 00:32:23.110
from such a small data point. The kids who
waited compared to the ones who grabbed get

00:32:23.110 --> 00:32:28.160
along better with their friends. They're still
able to defer gratification and pursue their

00:32:28.160 --> 00:32:36.370
goals. And the stunner was this. On their
SATs, they scored 210 points higher. It's

00:32:36.370 --> 00:32:41.290
at 16 or more than standard deviation. I told
this to the people at Princeton who make up

00:32:41.290 --> 00:32:48.480
the SAT, they were stunned. They said that's
as big as the difference we see between kids

00:32:48.480 --> 00:32:53.920
whose parents have--one parent has a graduate
degree, at least, and kids whose parents have

00:32:53.920 --> 00:33:00.179
no education. It's a huge difference. But
these were all children of Stanford folks,

00:33:00.179 --> 00:33:07.669
very high IQ family, so what's going on here?
What I think is going on is that impulsivity,

00:33:07.669 --> 00:33:16.250
agitation is the sign of the amygdala being
poorly inhibited. And kids who can't inhibit

00:33:16.250 --> 00:33:23.720
the amygdala do something or have a predicament
in learning situation which handicaps them.

00:33:23.720 --> 00:33:30.870
And, that is--remember what I said that when
the amygdala fires up, attention focuses on--and

00:33:30.870 --> 00:33:36.419
fixates actually on what is disturbing us,
you know, those other girls won't play with

00:33:36.419 --> 00:33:44.809
me. The melodramas of, you know, late elementary
school, whatever it may be. When that happens,

00:33:44.809 --> 00:33:50.630
it occupies the space of what's called the
“working memory.” Working memory is attention.

00:33:50.630 --> 00:33:56.430
You may remember from cognitive science the
working--the capacity of working memory is

00:33:56.430 --> 00:34:01.290
a magic number seven plus or minus two bits
of information. Well, if six of those bits

00:34:01.290 --> 00:34:05.410
of information have to do with those other
girls on the playground, it means you have

00:34:05.410 --> 00:34:11.669
one bit of information left for what the teacher
is saying to you. In other words, the SAT,

00:34:11.669 --> 00:34:16.069
which is an achievement test--it's not an
IQ test, an achievement test, it's a test

00:34:16.069 --> 00:34:24.149
of how much you learned over the course of
school--shows that if you are chronically

00:34:24.149 --> 00:34:32.039
handicapped in this ability, you will not
be able to learn. That's the bottom line from

00:34:32.039 --> 00:34:37.500
that study. And I think it's true in any situation,
in any work situation no matter what you're

00:34:37.500 --> 00:34:44.129
trying to do. The extent to which your mind
is preoccupied by distressing emotions is

00:34:44.129 --> 00:34:51.450
going to shrink cognitive capacity and make
it harder for you to do the work at hand.

00:34:51.450 --> 00:34:57.700
On the other hand, you could say that the
ability to inhibit distressing emotions from

00:34:57.700 --> 00:35:06.829
the amygdala is an enabler of cognitive capacity
because it leaves full attention available

00:35:06.829 --> 00:35:17.549
for what you're trying to do. So, let's look
at this from another angle, and that is if

00:35:17.549 --> 00:35:23.510
we were to--this is the way to map what's
happening with that HPA axis, the amygdala

00:35:23.510 --> 00:35:35.039
reactivity against performance in any domain.
So, here's

00:35:35.039 --> 00:35:48.920
performance and here's high and low HPA actively.
And the function between them is an inverted

00:35:48.920 --> 00:35:53.710
U. This has been known for a hundred years
in psychology. But what this really means

00:35:53.710 --> 00:36:03.700
is that when your HPA axis low, that's another
way of saying you're really bored. You're

00:36:03.700 --> 00:36:10.550
just not into it, not engaged. And if you
look at what's going on the brain, there is

00:36:10.550 --> 00:36:17.769
a very fuzzy pattern of activation. Basically,
your daydreams are as strong as your, okay,

00:36:17.769 --> 00:36:24.700
work cortex or whatever is going on. However,
the more engaged you get, the more motivated,

00:36:24.700 --> 00:36:30.369
the closer the deadline, the more interesting
the challenge, et cetera, the more cortisol--that's

00:36:30.369 --> 00:36:39.890
an indicator of HPA level--goes up and performance
goes up. There is an optimal zone here which

00:36:39.890 --> 00:36:46.109
is where you want to get and stay. This is
marked by what's called "flow." I don't know

00:36:46.109 --> 00:36:50.849
if you know the literature on flow. Some of
you do. But for those who don't, a study by

00:36:50.849 --> 00:36:56.920
a guy named [INDISTINCT] Mahalia--Mahalia
[INDISTINCT], actually. We call him Mike,

00:36:56.920 --> 00:37:03.650
for short. And he did something really interesting
several years ago. He studied people who were

00:37:03.650 --> 00:37:10.020
from many, many domains like brains surgeons,
basketball players, ballerinas, chess players,

00:37:10.020 --> 00:37:15.030
and so on, and he asked them to describe the
same thing. Tell me about the time you outdid

00:37:15.030 --> 00:37:19.770
yourself. Even you were surprised by how well
you did. And he realized that they're all

00:37:19.770 --> 00:37:27.099
describing phenomenologically the same brain
state. And it's a state in which your attention

00:37:27.099 --> 00:37:36.380
is fully focused, it's unbreakable, undistracted.
Your skills are really challenged by the demand

00:37:36.380 --> 00:37:42.150
but adequate, able to handle it and it feels
really good. He argues most of the things

00:37:42.150 --> 00:37:47.229
we do in life voluntarily we do because they
get us in a kind of a flow state. People who

00:37:47.229 --> 00:37:57.049
are--you know, when you really have--you know,
you're feeling buzzed and on, that's flow.

00:37:57.049 --> 00:38:05.609
One of the signs of it is feeling good. Damasio,
the same guy who consulted with a lawyer says

00:38:05.609 --> 00:38:14.039
that the feeling of enjoyment during an activity
is an indicator or proxy for optimal cognitive

00:38:14.039 --> 00:38:20.049
functioning. Optimal cognitive functioning
means your IQ is going as much as it can.

00:38:20.049 --> 00:38:24.390
You know, you can be creative. You can be
innovative. You can make associations. You

00:38:24.390 --> 00:38:34.609
can figure--solve problems at your best. Then,
however, if this continues, HPA activity continues,

00:38:34.609 --> 00:38:39.359
like you've got too much to do, too little
support, too little time, your life is falling

00:38:39.359 --> 00:38:48.569
apart, you feel frazzled. The neurophysiology
of frazzle is not--is that the HPA axis has

00:38:48.569 --> 00:38:56.430
gotten to a point where you're not only secreting
huge amount of cortisol but a big dollop of

00:38:56.430 --> 00:39:03.930
adrenaline and things fall apart cortically
because you're completely preoccupied by what's

00:39:03.930 --> 00:39:09.190
causing the frazzle, with just dealing with
the problems of life. So, the best place to

00:39:09.190 --> 00:39:16.819
be for cortisol effectiveness, to leverage
IQ skills is right there. And that is an emotional

00:39:16.819 --> 00:39:23.979
place. It's a place that is determined by
the emotional brain. So, in this sense, I'd

00:39:23.979 --> 00:39:31.079
argue that the self-mastery aspect of emotional
intelligence is catalytic for whatever cognitive

00:39:31.079 --> 00:39:37.880
abilities or talents you may have. Now, the
second two elements of emotional intelligence

00:39:37.880 --> 00:39:46.249
have to do with what's called the social brain.
The social brain is actually quite newly discovered.

00:39:46.249 --> 00:39:51.839
The discovery occurred when neuroscientists
decided to go beyond studying one brain and

00:39:51.839 --> 00:39:58.819
one body and one person and to look at what
happens in two brains, when two brains and

00:39:58.819 --> 00:40:03.140
two bodies and two people are interacting.
And they discovered circuits that they didn't

00:40:03.140 --> 00:40:08.630
even know existed. They discovered that the
brain is designed to connect, are wired to

00:40:08.630 --> 00:40:13.710
connect with the social brain of the other
person. It's the only part of human anatomy

00:40:13.710 --> 00:40:20.670
that is designed to attune to and regulate
itself according to the internal state of

00:40:20.670 --> 00:40:26.609
the other person. The big, the first big breakthrough
was something called "mirror neurons." Mirror

00:40:26.609 --> 00:40:35.420
neurons were discovered one day when some
Italian neuroscientists were mapping the motor

00:40:35.420 --> 00:40:41.549
cortex of a monkey and they're doing single
cell recordings. And, one afternoon, they

00:40:41.549 --> 00:40:49.599
were watching a neuron which only fired when
the monkey raised its arm. And, one day, the

00:40:49.599 --> 00:40:55.729
cell fired and the monkey hadn't moved. The
monkey's arm hadn't moved. And then they realized

00:40:55.729 --> 00:41:00.430
what's going on. It was a hot day and a lab
assistant had gone out to get an ice cream

00:41:00.430 --> 00:41:06.210
cone and every time he took a lick, the neuron
in the monkey's brain for doing that fired.

00:41:06.210 --> 00:41:13.069
That's what mirror neurons do in our brains.
It turns out that we have a diffused set,

00:41:13.069 --> 00:41:20.570
a ray of neurons, that elicit and activate
in us a mirror image of what the other person

00:41:20.570 --> 00:41:26.799
is doing, feeling, or intending. And this
is what allows us to synchronize interactions.

00:41:26.799 --> 00:41:37.550
This is what lets all the tacit, the tacit
decision rules that let an interaction go

00:41:37.550 --> 00:41:43.170
smoothly occur without our having to think
about it. The social brain operates from the

00:41:43.170 --> 00:41:47.640
unconscious level, beneath consciousness,
but it tells you when a conversation is about

00:41:47.640 --> 00:41:54.670
to end. In a room, when you got a group trying
to make a decision, social brains know the

00:41:54.670 --> 00:41:59.650
moment before someone announces it that we've
got a consensus here because we're reading

00:41:59.650 --> 00:42:04.729
everyone else's non-verbals all the time.
And then somebody says, “Oh, I guess, it

00:42:04.729 --> 00:42:09.660
looks like this," and everybody nods and then
you can leave, but it's done by the mirror

00:42:09.660 --> 00:42:17.739
neurons. Another thing that's very important
they find is that this means there is an emotional

00:42:17.739 --> 00:42:25.650
subtext to every human interaction. No matter
what's going on explicitly, tacitly, we're

00:42:25.650 --> 00:42:31.739
making each other feel a little worse or a
little better, or a lot worse or a lot better

00:42:31.739 --> 00:42:37.270
at this sign off level. They've looked at
top leaders in many different organizations,

00:42:37.270 --> 00:42:42.469
people who are identified by some hard metrics
within the organization that they're on top

00:42:42.469 --> 00:42:49.559
ten percent, and they watched how they interacted
with other people. And they found, interestingly,

00:42:49.559 --> 00:42:54.690
those most effective leaders laughed three
times more. In both, there was laughter three

00:42:54.690 --> 00:43:00.630
times more in that interaction than the mediocre
leaders. It turns out there are mirror neurons

00:43:00.630 --> 00:43:06.930
whose sole task is to spot a smile or a laugh
and make us smile and laugh in return. It's

00:43:06.930 --> 00:43:13.150
like an intimate brain to brain connection.
It builds rapport. If you look at what's going

00:43:13.150 --> 00:43:19.150
on during moments of rapport, you're seeing
the social brain in action. If you maunder

00:43:19.150 --> 00:43:24.729
the physiology and neurology of two people's
bodies while they're having a conversation,

00:43:24.729 --> 00:43:30.920
if things are awful, just not connecting,
we're not communicating here, the two bodies,

00:43:30.920 --> 00:43:36.400
the physiology is independent. But when people
feel really connected, this is really, you

00:43:36.400 --> 00:43:41.279
know, had a good rapport, we had good chemistry,
you see the bodies are going like this. And

00:43:41.279 --> 00:43:44.710
I'm talking about [INDISTINCT]. I'm talking
about physiology. I'm talking about autonomic

00:43:44.710 --> 00:43:53.749
function. We're on the same page. The ingredients
of rapport, a moment of rapport are three.

00:43:53.749 --> 00:44:00.489
Both people are paying full attention. You're
really attuned. The non-verbals look like

00:44:00.489 --> 00:44:07.150
a choreographed dance. You know, when I do
this, you do that. It's not anything we decide

00:44:07.150 --> 00:44:12.710
to do unless we're doing each other or offering
salsa lessons here, but other than that. But

00:44:12.710 --> 00:44:20.739
this is what creates a feeling of being well
connected. And the third thing that happened

00:44:20.739 --> 00:44:27.349
